The Week in Crypto Policy: Stablecoin Bill Comparison

George Leonardo

Oct 18, 2024 ⋅  7 min read

Key Insights

  • While major stablecoin proposals to date agree on high-level principles like establishing reserve, disclosure, and redemption policies, they diverge on specifics around who may issue stablecoins and roles for federal and state regulators.
  • Vice President Kamala Harris's campaign unveiled a new “Opportunity Agenda for Black Men,” which includes, as one of five agenda items: “supporting a regulatory framework for cryptocurrency and other digital assets so Black men who invest in and own these assets are protected.”

Stablecoin Bill Comparisons

If stablecoin legislation were somehow able to pass this Congress, any final bill would likely draw heavily from three major proposals published to date:

  • (1) House Financial Services Committee Chair Patrick McHenry’s Clarity for Payment Stablecoin Act (Reported out of committee on May 7, 2024; passed 34-16 in committee on 7.27.23; Rep. Ritchie Torres (D-NY) is a cosponsor).
  • (2) Senator Bill Hagerty’s Clarity for Payment Stablecoin Act (Discussion draft unveiled last Thursday; no cosponsors).
  • (3) Senator Cynthia Lummis's (R-WY) and Senator Kirsten Gillibrand's (D-NY) Lummis-Gillibrand Payment Stablecoin Act (Introduced on 10.26.23; no other cosponsors).

The analysis below compares and contrasts key provisions of these three bills.

As a preliminary caveat, the analysis is based on the latest publicly available text for each bill. While staff has likely continued to amend these drafts behind the scenes to address Member, constituent, and industry concerns, the analysis below is meant to highlight similarities and differences as a guidepost for identifying where roadblocks to compromise exist and where any final bill might land.

Who could issue stablecoins?

All three bills would provide federal and state pathways for stablecoin issuers. State-qualified issuers would be subject to minimum federal requirements, and in the case of Lummis-Gillibrand, subject to registration with the Federal Reserve. Senator Hagerty's bill and Lummis-Gillibrand would limit the state option to issuers under a $10 billion threshold.

While Lummis-Gillibrand limits issuers to non-depository state trust companies and certain depository institutions, Chair McHenry's bill and Senator Hagerty's bill would likely allow for a broader range of nonbank entities to issue stablecoins.

Note: Insured depository institution means an FDIC-insured bank, FDIC-insured savings association, or NCUA-insured credit union.

What rules would apply to issuers?

While specific requirements vary across bills, in general, all three proposals would require issuers to:

  • Back stablecoins with liquid reserve assets on at least a 1:1 basis;
  • Disclose reserve asset information;
  • Establish timely redemption processes;
  • Segregate customer property and not commingle customer property with company funds;
  • Comply with the Bank Secrecy Act;
  • Prohibit rehypothecation of reserve assets;
  • Limit activities to those related to stablecoin issuance and redemption.

In addition, all three bills would direct federal regulators to issue rules relating to capital, liquidity, and risk-management requirements.

Who would be the primary regulator?

Under Senator Hagerty's bill, the OCC would review bank and nonbank issuer applications at the federal level, but under McHenry's bill, the “primary federal regulator” would review issuer applications (other than state qualified issuers). Under McHenry's bill, the primary federal regulator of nonbanks would be the Fed, and the primary regulator of subsidiaries of insured depository institutions would be the banking agency that regulates the subsidiary's parent (e.g., Fed, FDIC, NCUA).

In all three bills, the Fed would retain at least some enforcement authority over state-approved issuers.

Algorithmic Stablecoins

Chair McHenry's bill and Senator Hagerty's bill would place a two-year moratorium on issuing new algorithmic stablecoins. During that period, Treasury would study algorithmic stablecoins, then report back to Congress with findings (including an analysis of types of algos, utilization, governance structure, consumer disclosures, and more).

Lummis-Gillibrand would place an outright ban on algos, though it also directs the Fed to establish a safe harbor.

Other Similarities & Differences

Similarities: All three bills include provisions to effectively repeal SAB 121 and direct federal regulators to coordinate on developing standards to promote interoperability.

One Major Difference: Lummis-Gillibrand would establish a detailed receivership framework for how the FDIC would wind down stablecoin issuers in financial distress (adapted from the Federal Deposit Insurance Act) (See § 9 of L-G). No similar section is included in McHenry's or Hagerty's bill.

Also, whereas Chair McHenry's bill and Senator Hagerty's bill would explicitly carve out “payment stablecoins” from securities laws, Lummis-Gillibrand does not include such a provision.

Look Ahead

  • Election: 17 days away.
  • Start of lame duck: 24 days away.

Quick Hits

2024 Presidential

On Monday, Vice President Harris unveiled an “Opportunity Agenda for Black Men.”

  • ​Text.

One of five agenda items reads:

  • “Supporting a regulatory framework for cryptocurrency and other digital assets so Black men who invest in and own these assets are protected.” Doc at 1.
  • For context, the other four items are: (1) providing 1 million fully forgivable loans to entrepreneurs, (2) championing education programs, (3) launching a “National Health Equity Initiative,” and (4) legalizing recreational marijuana.

The document also says Harris will work on “enabling Black men who hold digital assets to benefit from financial innovation,” adding:

  • “More than 20% of Black Americans own or have owned cryptocurrency assets. Vice President Harris appreciates the ways in which new technologies can broaden access to banking and financial services. She will make sure owners of and investors in digital assets benefit from a regulatory framework so that Black men and others who participate in this market are protected.” Doc at 3.

Later in the week, the Harris campaign clarified for the Wall Street Journal that policies outlined in the Opportunity Agenda for Black Men would actually be open to all Americans on a race-neutral basis.

Courts

SEC v. Ripple

  • In a new filling, the SEC said it will appeal the following issues to the Second Circuit:
  • ​Filing.
  • Note: The SEC is not appealing Judge Torres's ruling that XRP itself is not a security.
  • Not everyone believes the SEC met its filing deadline.

Bitnomial

  • Bitnomial sued the SEC in the Northern District of Illinois, asking the court to confirm the SEC cannot prohibit the listing, trading, purchasing, or selling of XRP futures on Bitnomial's exchange. Bitnomial argues that because XRP itself is not a security and secondary market sales of XRP are not securities, XRP futures are not security futures, and thus not subject to SEC jurisdiction.
    • ​Filing.
    • ​Background by Katten Muchin Rosenman LLP (Bitnomial's counsel).

Coinbase

  • Coinbase filed a motion for partial summary judgment in a case seeking documents from the SEC regarding the agency's approach to digital assets.
    • ​Summary & Background by The DeFi Defender, Carlo D'Angelo.
